05/06/2003
VIENNA, Austria -- Paddy Ashdown, the chief international officer in Bosnia and Herzegovina, told the OSCE Permanent Council on Wednesday (4 June) that he was concerned about the possibility of a severe economic crisis in the country.He highlighted the need for sweeping reforms and the imposition of curbs on government spending.
Ashdown said there are 11 duplicating government structures in the country.
"Sixty per cent of government spending goes to the government.
No state can survive when it spends so much on governing itself and so little on its citizens," Ashdown said.
(AFP - 04/06/03)
